2 A Deterministic Infinite Memory Model

2.1 What Causes Model Collapse ?

Tail Cutting.

4 A Tailed Bigram Model

Mitigation:

Appendix G Details and Results on Transformer Arithmetic Experiments

Charton (2023) trains sequence-to-sequence transformers to predict the greatest common divisor (GCD) of two positive integers, encoded as sequences of digits in some base BğµBitalic_B. He observes that model predictions are deterministic: for any pair (a,b)ğ‘ğ‘(a,b)( italic_a , italic_b ) with GCD kğ‘˜kitalic_k, the model predicts a single value fâ¢(k)ğ‘“ğ‘˜f(k)italic_f ( italic_k ). Predictions are correct (i.e. fâ¢(k)=kğ‘“ğ‘˜ğ‘˜f(k)=kitalic_f ( italic_k ) = italic_k) when the GCD is a product of divisors of the base, or of small primes. In all other case, the model prediction is the largest correct prediction (i.e. lğ‘™litalic_l such that fâ¢(l)=lğ‘“ğ‘™ğ‘™f(l)=litalic_f ( italic_l ) = italic_l) that divides kğ‘˜kitalic_k. The list of correct predictions â„’â„’\mathcal{L}caligraphic_L varies with the encoding base BğµBitalic_B. For instance, for B=10ğµ10B=10italic_B = 10, after 300 million examples, the model correctly predicts â„’={1,2,4,5,8,10,16,20,25,40,50,80,100â¢â€¦}â„’1245810162025405080100â€¦\mathcal{L}=\{1,2,4,5,8,10,16,20,25,40,50,80,100...\}caligraphic_L = { 1 , 2 , 4 , 5 , 8 , 10 , 16 , 20 , 25 , 40 , 50 , 80 , 100 â€¦ }, the GCD of 20202020 and 30303030 will be correctly predicted as 10101010, but the GCD of 210210210210 and 140140140140 will be incorrectly predicted as 10101010 (instead of 70707070).

Appendix H Details of Experiments with Llama2

ëŒ€í˜• ì–¸ì–´ ëª¨ë¸(LLM)ì˜ ì˜ì—­ì—ì„œ, ê¸°ì¡´ì˜ ì ‘ê·¼ë²•ì€ ì‚¬ì „ í›ˆë ¨ ë° ë¯¸ì„¸ ì¡°ì • íŒ¨ëŸ¬ë‹¤ì„ì„ í¬í•¨í•œë‹¤. ì˜ˆë¥¼ ë“¤ì–´ GPT-3ëŠ” ë‹¤ì–‘í•œ ì¶œì²˜ì—ì„œ ì•½ 45TBì˜ í…ìŠ¤íŠ¸ ë°ì´í„°ì— ëŒ€í•œ ì‚¬ì „ êµìœ¡ì„ ë°›ëŠ”ë‹¤. ì´ëŸ¬í•œ ê´‘ë²”ìœ„í•œ ì‚¬ì „ í›ˆë ¨ì€ ì œë¡œ ìƒ· í•™ìŠµ, ì†Œìƒ· í•™ìŠµ ë˜ëŠ” ë¯¸ì„¸ ì¡°ì •ê³¼ ê°™ì€ ë°©ë²•ì„ ì‚¬ìš©í•˜ì—¬ ë‹¤ì–‘í•œ ë‹¤ìš´ìŠ¤íŠ¸ë¦¼ ì‘ì—…ì— ëŒ€í•œ ê°•ë ¥í•œ ê¸°ëŠ¥ì„ ì œê³µí•œë‹¤. ìš°ë¦¬ì˜ ì—°êµ¬ëŠ” í˜„ëŒ€ 'í•©ì„± ë°ì´í„° ì‹œëŒ€'ì— ê°€ê¹Œìš´ ì‹œë‚˜ë¦¬ì˜¤ì—ì„œ ëª¨ë¸ ë¶•ê´´ í˜„ìƒì„ í‰ê°€í•œë‹¤.

Instructions for reporting errors

We are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile support. To report errors in the HTML that will help us improve conversion and rendering, choose any of the methods listed below:

  • Click the "Report Issue" button.
  • Open a report feedback form via keyboard, use "Ctrl + ?".
  • Make a text selection and click the "Report Issue for Selection" button near your cursor.
  • You can use Alt+Y to toggle on and Alt+Shift+Y to toggle off accessible reporting links at each section.

Our team has already identified the following issues. We appreciate your time reviewing and reporting rendering errors we may not have found yet. Your efforts will help us improve the HTML versions for all readers, because disability should not be a barrier to accessing research. Thank you for your continued support in championing open access for all.

Have a free development cycle? Help support accessibility at arXiv! Our collaborators at LaTeXML maintain a list of packages that need conversion, and welcome developer contributions.
